segments.text: Okay, Mr. Peters, you were going to tell me something about your great-grandparents or grandparents or whatever you remembered about where they came from and what brought them into this area.
I can't, like I say, my own grandparents, as far as I know, were raised right here.
But I've heard them talking about grandparents on one side
where one of them was, Grandpa Peters was a German fellow, and his wife was Irish.
And I heard my daddy say that, you know, they couldn't talk plain English.
But I guess that's far back.
Like I said, my other grandparents, as far as I know, they were raised right here around Bradstown County, I guess.
Did you go—you said you went to school, some of the earlier grades in school.
Did you go here?
Yeah.
Tell me something about where the schoolhouse was and who taught or whatever you remember about that.
Well, the first school I ever went to was—my only school I ever went to was right down here.
What community center?
Oh, it's about two miles from here, I reckon, two and a half, three miles.
And that's where I started and that's where I wound up, right down there.
10, you tell me something about school.
What was it like then, as best you remember?
Well, them days, they had one teacher to have several grades, you know.
And this school down here, we went through the ninth grade.
And they had three teachers.
You remember who they were?
Yeah, I remember some of them.
Mr. Rich MacDonald, Mr. Barden, and Mr. Barden's wife, and they were devoused in Buckhannon.
I know when I was in, first year I was in school, trying to learn my letters, they tell it on me and I know it so, but they laugh at me yet about it.
When I got the S, that night before, Papa told me, he said, you ought to remember that, it looked like a snake.
And the next day I called,
They called it S. I told them, no, that's a snake.
My papa said, that's a snake.
But they were strict teachers them days.
I mean, a student, you didn't talk back to your teacher.
What would happen?
What would happen?
Well, them teachers'd tear you up them days.
They sure would.
And then, another thing, if you...

better keep it a secret until your daddy get older when you got home because when when you got out of line when you got to look at the two lemon days why they figured you know if you ever fought with a man it was always for a day but i just started saying that's about all i had to say about it
You know, my father can tell, has told me before of getting up and going hunting or doing the chores or whatever, and then going to school and coming home and finishing up.
Did you have to do the same thing?
Yeah.
Yeah, my job was feeding the horses.
Mews back then, they, you know, farmed with mews and had horses, took eggs and canned them, plowed them too, worked them to the buggy.
We had a, my daddy had a carriage, you know what that is?
Mm-hmm.
and two-seated buggy thing and carried with his top on it and worked two horses to it.
And that's the way we went to church them days and of course town too.
We'd go to town about time.
But I've seen the day when a neighbor down below us here would come by here with the roaches to bed in the winter before Christmas.
I've seen that happen.
Come out here with a four-mule wagon, you know, four mules to one wagon, and my sister and my mother would get in with them and they'd go on the run and do the Christmas shopping.
But that was a pretty tough day so far as getting in and out is concerned.
I bet it was.
That brings up another point I'd be very interested in knowing.
I have heard my parents and my grandparents tell me for a long time that Christmases today just aren't what they used to be.
Now, I'd be really interested in knowing about what Christmas was to you in this area when you were a kid.
Well, we had a lot of fun.
Like I said a while ago, we had those parties, you know, over during Christmas.
Play parties.
We had a lot of fun in those days.
Just lots of fun.
Doing the first one thing, playing pranks on people.
Well, I can't remember what the word was.
You're like me.
You don't want to tell your pranks, do you?
No, I can't remember too much about it.
I know we had a big time.
You talked about farming and ranching earlier.

uh what did most people do which of those two in uh say in 1910 or you mean when the ranchers are far right more of the farm more of the farm okay that brings up a very interesting point then uh the invention of a lot of farm machinery
Must have changed the way people farm tremendously.
Oh, yeah.
I'm sure you know something about that.
Can you remember when the first tractor came in or when the first combine or whatever?
I'm sure they used to pick cotton here by hand, didn't they?
Oh, yeah.
That's the only way you can plow it with mules, too.
When I was a kid, they plowed one mule.
And when they're breaking the land, they'd make four furs.
They'd plow right down the side of the cotton stalk, you know, like here, and throw the fur this way, and then they'd come back over here on this side.
And then they'd go back then and make two furs to run that middle there.
And everybody used just one mule every day to break land.
But then later on, they got to breaking with two mules and plow a little deeper, you know, and break the land a little deeper.
And then later on in that, well, they got to using three mules to break land with a middle buster and really put it down in the ground to plow, you know, to make it deep.
But I don't remember what year the tractors come in there, but we didn't own a tractor.
We didn't own a tractor till, well, when I worked for my brother over there at some time between 33 and 43,
that he bought a tractor when I was working for him.
I reckon we had an old tractor around somewhere close to 1950.
But it used to be an old wagon, walking.
Of course, I plowed a steer once.
That's the only time I ever done that.
How was that?
Well, my granddaddy

had a family that got sick, the man did, you know, the colored fellas on the working farm, and he's plowing steers, and we put a collar upside down on the steer, a horse collar, and was plowing cotton, and you know, he'd plow dirt and cotton, we'd call it, we'd have to plow up the next, this row, and this way, and then have it come down that way, and I plowed that old steer over there about, oh, about two weeks, I reckon,
But that's the only steer I ever plowed in my life.
I plowed mules and horses and things like that.
That's the only steer I ever plowed.
And then the tanks, everything we did, we did with teams.
And during that Depression, they, we tell you about, they did some road work, the county did.
And I know there's several that did teamwork on the county building that rolled up, you know.
Well, there's several of us around the community here got a job there with scrapers, you know, first team and driver's team.
Wasn't getting much, but they'd show a lot of money them days.
How much were you getting?
I can't remember.
Seemed to me like about $3 a day.
Seemed like.
But them days, just a little money could... Now, I worked.
for $50 a month, went to work for $50 a month in 33.
And I had an old car, and I fed my family.
I had three children.
Fed my family, and we had that old car to come back and forth once in a while then.
How much was gasoline then?
I can't remember.
Not anything like it is today?
Oh, no, it is.
I got to talk about that now.
It's been here.
I don't know if it's been here.
or maybe 12 to 10, 12 years, but it's set when it come here on 26th century gallon, you know, and never had been changed.
Can you remember the first time you ever rode an automobile?
No, I don't think we can.
When was the first time you ever saw one?
Well, I guess that and on that street up there about the first night or so.
Man, that is a show back in them days when you could see a automobile.
I went one time with my granddaddy and grandmother out towards Crystal City, out in that section of the country.
My granddaddy's second wife and his first wife died.
And she had a son that lived out there, and we went with them out there, three or four of us kids, to visit with them.
And of course, that was back when they were selling, you know, land agents.
They sold tons.
The warrants had a lot of land down in that country.
But they carried my granddaddy around.
We was riding with him.
And this fellow smoking a cigar, I'll never forget that.
And it had tops them days, you know, it wasn't like it is now.
In the summertime, just push the top back over it.
This fella smoking a cigar and the ashes blowed off in my eye.
I'd like to kill me.
I sure have been watching anybody smoking when I was riding behind them sentient.
You know this lady that works out at the entomology building with me, this kitty used to be Rozier.
You remember thinking about her family in this area?
But no, they lived in the joining community.
I know Kitty all right, and I've been knowing her a long time, but I didn't know her before she was married or anything like that.
Do you know anything about why her folks came to this area?
No, I sure don't.
No, I don't.
Well, is there any particular thing, again, that really...
impresses you, or has impressed you, in the past about Bryan College Station.
For instance, when did you first become acquainted with the university?
And to know, see, there's some people out there, or the university's certainly not like it used to be.
Can you give me some changes you've noticed in it?
Well, I reckon I've been around college as little as anybody has lived.
Lived here as long as I ever, maybe less than anybody.
But...
Brian, back yonder, you know, we drove cattle everywhere.
You didn't haul cattle anywhere.
You didn't have no way to haul them.
You didn't have a road to haul them on.
Chunks of nothing.
But we'd drive cattle to town, Brian, and out there where the pasture land end was, it just, how you just think it was going to be.
Of course, there wouldn't be no way you could drive cattle out there now.
But them ladies, them days, would get out on the yard and have a broom.
They didn't want to keep cattle up on the lawn.
But they drove everything around.
You remember any big events that have occurred around Texas A&M out here that you remember reading about or hearing about in say in the 1900 and between 1900 and 1910?
I can't remember.
Do you remember any about what the guys did out there during the war?
Well, no I don't remember much about that.
The preceding has been a recorded interview with Mr. D.L.
Doug Peters, lifetime resident of the Brazos Valley of College Station, rancher, 77 years of age.
The interview was conducted on March 11, 1975, by Carl S. Barfield.
